04723nam a22006735i 9780292729995DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927299957 a10.7560/7238322doi  a(DE-B1597)587159  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF3429b.M7213 2011 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a299.81132221 aMolina, Cristóbal de, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAccount of the Fables and Rites of the Incas /cCristóbal de Molina; ed. by Vania Smith-Oka, Gabriel E. Cantarutti, Brian S. Bauer. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Translators’ Notes -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Life and Times of Cristóbal de Molina -- tIntroduction -- tForeword: Account of the Fables and Rites of the Incas -- tChapter 1: Introduction -- tChapter 2: Origin Myths 4 -- tChapter 3: Of Quipus and Inca Yupanqui -- tChapter 4: Th e Sorcerers -- tChapter 5: Th e Rituals of the Months of the Year -- tChapter 6: Th e Ayuscay, Rutuchico, and Quicochico Rituals -- tChapter 7: The Capacocha -- tChapter 8: Taqui Onqoy -- tAppendix: Editions of Cristóbal de Molina’s Account of the Fables and Rites of the Incas (Relación de las fábulas y ritos de los incas) -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOnly a few decades after the Spanish conquest of Peru, the third Bishop of Cuzco, Sebastián de Lartaún, called for a report on the religious practices of the Incas. The report was prepared by Cristóbal de Molina, a priest of the Hospital for the Natives of Our Lady of Succor in Cuzco and Preacher General of the city. Molina was an outstanding Quechua speaker, and his advanced language skills allowed him to interview the older indigenous men of Cuzco who were among the last surviving eyewitnesses of the rituals conducted at the height of Inca rule. Thus, Molina's account preserves a crucial first-hand record of Inca religious beliefs and practices. This volume is the first English translation of Molina's Relación de las fábulas y ritos de los incas since 1873 and includes the first authoritative scholarly commentary and notes. The work opens with several Inca creation myths and descriptions of the major gods and shrines (huacas). Molina then discusses the most important rituals that occurred in Cuzco during each month of the year, as well as rituals that were not tied to the ceremonial calendar, such as birth rituals, female initiation rites, and marriages. Molina also describes the Capacocha ritual, in which all the shrines of the empire were offered sacrifices, as well as the Taqui Ongoy, a millennial movement that spread across the Andes during the late 1560s in response to growing Spanish domination and accelerated violence against the so-called idolatrous religions of the Andean peoples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aInca mythology. 0aIncasxRites and ceremonies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBauer, Brian S.1 aBauer, Brian S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Brian S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCantarutti, Gabriel E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith-Oka, Vania, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292729995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292729995/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles 